ic of Lakotah proposal|Republic of Lakotah]]\n** Ethnic group: [[Lakota people]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Texas.svg|22px|border]] [[Texas]]\n{{Main article|Texas secession movements}}\n* Proposed state: [[File:Flag of Texas.svg|22px|border]] [[Republic of Texas]]\n** Pressure groups: [[Texas Nationalist Movement]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetnm.org/}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flag of Vermont.svg|22px|border]] [[Vermont]]\n* Proposed state: Restoration of the [[File:Flag_of_the_Vermont_Republic.svg|22px|border]] [[Vermont Republic]]\n* Political party: Vermont Independence Party<ref>[http://www.wcax.com/story/19502928/vt-independence-party-to-meet-in-montpelier Vt. Independence Party to meet in Montpelier], [[WCAX-TV]] News, September 12, 2012.</ref><ref>[http://www.7dvt.com/vermont-independence-party?filter1&#91;date&#93;=2010-01-15&filter1&#91;time&#93;=00%3A00&filter2&#91;date&#93;=2010-01-15&filter2&#91;time&#93;=23%3A59&timeframe=future Vermont Independence Party convention], Seven Days newspaper, September 2012.</ref>\n* Pressure group: [[File:Flag_of_the_Vermont_Republic.svg|22px|border]] [[Second Vermont Republic]] and the [[Green Mountain Anarchist Collective]]\n\n\n===Territories===\n{{flag|Puerto Rico}}\n{{main article|Independence movement in Puerto Rico}}\n* Cultural group: [[Puerto Rican people]]\n** Proposed state: {{flag|Puerto Rico|name=Republic of Puerto Rico}}\n*** Political party: [[Puerto Rican Independence Party]] (PIP)\n*** Pressure group: [[Puerto Rican Nationalist Party]], [[Movimiento Independentista Nacional Hostosiano]] (MINH), [[Socialist Front (Puerto Rico)|Socialist Front]] (FS)\n*** Militant organization: [[Boricua Popular Army]] (Macheteros), [[Cadets of the Republic]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Other===\n[[File:Flag of the Confederate States of America (1865).svg|border|22x22px]] [[Confederate States of America]]\n{{main article|Neo-Confederate}}\n* Proposed state: Confederate States of America or [[Southern United States]]\n** Pressure groups: [[League of the South]], [https://freeflorida.org The Florida League of the South], [https://northfloridals.org The North Florida Chapter League of the South], New Confederate Army\n\n==French Overseas Departments and Collectivities==\n{{Main|Secession in France}}\n\n[[Image:Flag of the Front National de Lib\u00e9ration de la Martinique.svg|22px|border]] [[Martinique]]\n* Proposed state: Republic of Martinique\n** Political party: [[Martinican Progressive Party]], [[Image:Bandera del MIM.svg|22px|border]] [[Martinican Independence Movement]]\n\n[[Image:FLNG.svg|22px|border]] [[Guadeloupe]] \n* Proposed state: Republic of Guadeloupe\n** Political party: [[United Guadeloupe, Solidary and Responsible]], [[Progressive Democratic Party of Guadeloupe]], [[Plural Left (Guadeloupe)|Plural Left]] and the [[Guadeloupean Objective]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Saint-Martin (fictional).svg|22px|border]] [[Collectivity of Saint Martin|Saint Martin]]\n* Proposed state: Republic of Saint Martin\n** Political party: [[Rally Responsibility Success]], [[Succeed Saint Martin]], [[Union for Progress (Saint Martin)|Union for Progress]], [[Union for Progress (Saint Martin)|Union for Progress]] and the [[Democratic Alliance for Saint Martin]]\n\n{{Flagicon|France}} [[Saint Barthelemy]]\n* Proposed state: Republic of Saint Barthelemy\n** Political party: [[Saint Barth First!]], [[All United for Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]], [[Action Balance and Transparence]] and [[Together for Saint Barth\u00e9lemy]]\n\n{{Flagicon|France}} [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon]]\n* Proposed State: Republic of Saint Pierre and Miquelon\n** Political party: [[Archipelago Tomorrow]], [[Together for the Future]], [[Saint Pierre and Miquelon 2000]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Lists of active separatist movements]]\n* [[List of historical separatist movements]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n{{Separatist movements per continent}}\n{{Secession in Countries}}\n{{Irredentism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Active Separatist Movements In North America, List Of}}\n[[Category:North America-related lists|Separatist Movements, Active]]\n[[Category:Disputed territories in North America|Separatist Movements In North America, Active]]\n[[Category:Lists of active separatist movements|North America]]\n[[Category:Society-related lists|Separatist Movements In North America, Active]]\n", "name_user": "ExplodingPoPUps", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_active_separatist_movements_in_North_America"}
{"title_page": "Kapiolani Medical Center for Women and Children", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Kapiolani Medical Center for Women and Children\n| Org/Group  = <!-- optional -->\n| Image      = <!-- optional -->\n| Caption    = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo       = Kapiolani Medical Center logo.svg\n| Location   = [[Honolulu, Hawaii|Honolulu]]\n| Region     = Oahu\n| State      = Hawaii\n| Country    = US\n| Coordinates =\n| HealthCare = Community\n| Funding    = <!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public -->\n| Type       = Non-profit\n| Speciality = [[Maternity]] and [[Pediatrics]]\n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency  = Yes\n| Helipad     = <!-- No -->\n| Affiliation = <!-- No -->\n| Patron      = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| Network     = [[Hawaii Pacific Health]]\n| Beds        = 207\n| Founded     = 1978\n| Closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| Website     = http://www.kapiolani.org <!-- 'None' or http URL -->\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n\n[[File:A Woman with a Baby at the Kapiolani Maternity Home.jpg|thumb|A woman with a baby at the Kapiolani Maternity Home around the twenty-first anniversary in 1912]]\n[[File:Obama birth announcement.jpg|150px|thumb|[[Barack Obama]] birth announcement]]\n[[File:Mom and Premature Baby at Kapiolani.jpg|thumb|A new mother holds her baby who was [[Preterm birth|born 10 weeks premature]] at Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center]]\n'''Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children''' is part of [[Hawaii Pacific Health]]'s network of hospitals. It is located in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], within the residential inner-city district of [[Makiki]]. Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center is Hawaii's only [[children's hospital]] with a  team of physicians and nurses and specialized technology trained specifically to care for children, from infants to young adults. It is the state's only 24-hour pediatric [[emergency department]], pediatric intensive care unit and adolescent unit.\n\nThe facility was founded by [[Queen Kapiolani|Queen Kapi{{okina}}olani]] as the Kapi{{okina}}olani Maternity Home in 1890 for which she held bazaars and [[luau]]s to raise $8,000 needed to start the Home. It has since changed its name several times. Kauikeolani Children\u2019s Hospital opened in 1909 named for [[Emma Kauike\u014dlani Wilcox|Emma Kauike\u014dlani Napoleon Mahelona]] (1862\u20131931), the wife of [[Albert Spencer Wilcox]] (1844\u20131919).<ref>{{cite book |author=Nellist, George F. (ed.) |year=1925 |chapter= Albert Spencer Wilcox |title=The story of Hawaii and its builders |location=Honolulu |publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |chapter-url=http://files.usgwarchives.net/hi/statewide/bios/wilcox64bs.txt |accessdate=September 26, 2010}}</ref>  In 1978, it merged with Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital to become Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children.<ref>{{cite web |author= |year=2009 |title=100 years of caring for children |url=http://www.kapiolanigift.org/timeline/index.html |location=Honolulu |publisher=Kapiolani Health Foundation |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Kessing, Alice |date=August 19, 2009 |title=Queen Kapi'olani's living gift to island keiki |newspaper=[[MidWeek]] |location=Honolulu |url=http://www.midweek.com/content/story/midweek_coverstory/queen_kapiolanis_living_gift_to_island_keiki/P1/ |accessdate=October 1, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430151312/http://www.midweek.com/content/story/midweek_coverstory/queen_kapiolanis_living_gift_to_island_keiki/P1 |archive-date=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Hawaii Pacific Health |date=August 26, 2009 |title=Kapi'olani Hospital's '100 years \u2013 over 1 million lives' celebration |location=Honolulu |publisher=[[KGMB]] |url=http://kgmb9.com/main/content/view/20536/108/ |accessdate=October 1, 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Historical timeline==\n\n===Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital===\n* In 1884, [[Victoria Kinoiki Kekaulike|Princess Kekaulike]] died and willed her home, ''Ululani'', as the site of a proposed [[maternity home]] to help Hawaiian mothers.\n* In 1890, after the princess's sister, [[Queen Kapiolani|Queen Kapi{{okina}}olani]], raised $8,000 through bazaars and luaus, she founded the '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Home of the Ho{{okina}}oulu and Ho{{okina}}ola Lahui Society''' (society to propagate and perpetuate the race), located at Beretania and Makiki streets, to provide a maternity home for Hawaiian women. The five-bedroom home was opened on June 14, 1890, by [[Kal\u0101kaua|King Kal\u0101kaua]] and Queen Kapi{{okina}}olani. Only six babies were born at the home the first year since Native Hawaiian women remained suspicious of doctors and institutions.\n* In 1917, the society purchased the adjacent August Dreier property southeast of ''Ululani'' on Beretania Street.\n* In 1918, the home moved to a two-story house with 25 beds at 1538 S. Beretania Street, changed its name to the '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Maternity Home''', and opened its doors to women of other than Hawaiian descent.\n* In 1927, the trustees purchased the property of Dr. John Whitney on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham streets to build a new maternity home.\n* In 1928, groundbreaking ceremonies for the new maternity home were held on June 28.\n* In 1929, the home moved on March 26 to a new larger building with 50 beds (in twenty-two private rooms, four 2-bedrooms, and two wards) located on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham streets and expanded its functions to include non-infectious gynecological problems. The original Whitney home was converted to a nurses' home.\n* In 1931, its name was changed to the '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Maternity and Gynecological Hospital'''.\n* In 1939, after purchasing the adjacent Spalding property south of the hospital on Punahou Street, the Spalding home was converted into a nurses' home named the Kekaulike Nurses' Home.\n* In 1945, the hospital, at 1611 Bingham Street, finished construction of the two-story Ewa wing that doubled its capacity to 110 beds.\n* In 1957, the hospital completed a new and enlarged nursery.\n* In 1961, future [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] was born in the hospital on August 4.<ref>{{cite news |author=Maraniss, David |date=August 24, 2008 |title=Though Obama had to leave to find himself, it is Hawaii that made his rise possible |newspaper=The Washington Post |page=A22 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/23/AR2008082301620.html |accessdate=June 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Serafin, Peter |date=March 21, 2004 |title=Punahou grad stirs up Illinois politics |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2004/03/21/news/story4.html |accessdate=June 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Hoover, Will |date=November 9, 2008 |title=Obama's Hawaii boyhood homes drawing gawkers |newspaper=The Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Nov/09/ln/hawaii811090361.html |accessdate=June 28, 2009 |quote=Birthplaces and boyhood homes of U.S. presidents have been duly noted and honored}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |date=January 24, 2009 |title=Kapi' olani Health Foundation, The Centennial Dinner January 24, 2009 |location=Honolulu |publisher=Kapiolani Health Foundation |url=http://www.kapiolanigift.org/the_centennial_dinner.aspx |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Nakaso, Dan |date=December 22, 2008 | title=Twin sisters, Obama on parallel paths for years |newspaper=The Honolulu Advertiser |page=B1 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Dec/22/ln/hawaii812220320.html |accessdate=March 1, 2009}}</ref>\n* In 1966, the hospital completed a new four-story Lani Ward Booth wing on Punahou Street, with the top two floors left as shells, capacity remained at 110 beds.\n* In 1970, the hospital finished the fourth floor of the Lani Booth wing on Punahou Street, capacity increased to 138 beds.\n* In 1971, its name was changed to '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital'''.\n* In 1974, the hospital began a major rebuilding project, adding an eleven-story hospital and medical office tower on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham Streets, a three-story building, and a parking structure for a combined Kapi{{okina}}olani/Children's Medical Center.\n* In 1976, the new tower was dedicated and Kapi{{okina}}olani patients were moved to its second and fourth floors.\n* In 1977, a section of the original 1929 building was torn down and tiles from its roof were sold to commemorate the 145,000 babies born under it from 1929 to 1977.\n\n===Kauikeolani Children's Hospital===\n[[File:Kapiolani Neonatal ICU.jpg|thumb|The [[Neonatal intensive-care unit|Neonatal Intensive Care Unit]] (NICU) at Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center]]\n* In 1908, [[Albert Spencer Wilcox]] (1844\u20131919) gave $55,000 and other private subscribers gave an additional $50,000 to buy several acres of land and erect a two-story comparatively small, homelike children's hospital (with preference given to Hawaiian children) at 226 N. Kuakini Street, named after Wilcox's wife, Emma Kauikeolani Napoliean Mahelona (1862\u20131931). A maternity service was soon after added to the hospital.\n* In 1929, the maternity service at the hospital was discontinued.\n* In 1950, a new, modern two-story hospital building with a capacity of 100 beds replaced the original building.\n* In 1953, the Rehabilitation Center of Hawaii was established by the Kauikeolani Children's Hospital Foundation.\n* In 1969, the rehabilitation center was renamed the Pacific Institute of Rehabilitation Medicine.\n* In 1975, the rehabilitation center separated from Kauikeolani Children's Hospital to become the independent Rehabilitation Hospital of the Pacific, which expanded into the 1950 Kauikeolani Children's Hospital building after the latter relocated to Kapi{{okina}}olani/Children's Medical Center on September 15, 1978.\n\n===Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children===\n* In 1976, Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital and Kauikenolani Children's Hospital began a protracted, decade-long merger.\n* In 1978, Kauikeolani Children's Hospital moved into the new eleven-story (226-bed, 108-bassinet) '''Kapi{{okina}}olani/Children's Medical Center''' tower located at 1319 Punahou Street on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham streets\u2014initially with separate entrances for the pediatricians on Bingham Street and the obstetricians on Punahou Street.\n* In 1984, the medical staff and board of directors of the two former hospitals were merged.\n* In 1986, the two former hospitals formally completed their merger.\n* In 1989, Kapi{{okina}}olani purchased for $76 million the new 116-bed [[Kapiolani Medical Center at Pali Momi|Pali Momi Medical Center]] in [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], built by Health Care International, six months after it opened.\n* In 2001, Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children and Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center at Pali Momi in Aiea merged with [[Wilcox Health|Wilcox Memorial Hospital]] in [[Lihue, Hawaii|Lihue]] on the Hawaiian island of [[Kauai]] (founded in 1938) and the [[Straub Clinic & Hospital]] (founded in 1921) on King Street, under a new parent company, [[Hawaii Pacific Health]].\n\n== References ==\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book |author1=Yardley, Maili |author2=Rogers, Miriam |year=1984 |title=The history of Kapiolani Hospital |location=Honolulu |publisher=Topgallant Pub. Co. |isbn=0-914916-62-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/hawaiicooksislan00yard }}\n* {{cite book |author=Schnack, Ferdinand J.H. |year=1915 |title=The aloha guide: the standard handbook of Honolulu and the Hawaiian Islands |url=https://archive.org/details/alohaguidestand02schngoog |location=Honolulu |publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=[https://archive.org/details/alohaguidestand02schngoog/page/n154 150] |oclc=12657550}}\n* {{cite book |author=Allen, Gwenfread E. |year=1950 |title=Hawaii's war years, 1941\u20131945 |location=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii |page=339 |isbn=0-8371-5331-X}}\n* {{cite book |author=Catton, Margaret Mary Louise |year=1959 |title=Social service in Hawaii |location=Palo Alto, Calif. |publisher=Pacific Books |pages=99\u2013101, 102\u2013103, 289 |oclc=1970774}}\n* {{cite book |author=Lewis, Frances R. Hegglund |year=1969 |title=History of nursing in Hawaii |location=Node, Wyo. |publisher=Germann-Kilmer |pages=68, 104 |oclc=11323826}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Bowers, John Z. |author2=Purcell, Elizabeth |year=1978 |title=New medical schools at home and abroad: report of a Macy conference |location=New York |publisher=Josiah Macy, Jr. Foundation |page=73 |isbn=0-914362-26-7}}\n* {{cite book |author=Lipp, Martin R. |year=1991 |title=Medical landmarks USA: a travel guide to historic sites, architectural gems, remarkable museums and libraries, and other places of health related interest |location=New York |publisher=McGraw-Hill, Health Professions Div. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/medicallandmarks0000lipp/page/310 310\u2013311] |isbn=0-07-037974-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/medicallandmarks0000lipp/page/310 }}\n* {{cite web |author=. |date=March 8, 2010 |title=Final Environmental Assessment (FEA): Proposed improvements to Kapliolani Medical Center for Women and Children (December 2009) |location=Honolulu |publisher=Office of Environmental Quality Control, Department of Health, State of Hawaii |url=http://oeqc.doh.hawaii.gov/Shared%20Documents/EA_and_EIS_Online_Library/Oahu/2010s/2010-03-08-OA-FEA-Kapiolani-Med-Center-Imp.pdf |accessdate=April 28, 2011}}\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official|http://www.kapiolani.org/women-and-children/default.aspx }}\n\n{{Hawaii Pacific Health}}\n\n{{coord|21.2998|N|157.8335|W|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Children's hospitals in the United States]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Honolulu]]\n[[Category:1890 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Women's hospitals]]\n[[Category:Barack Obama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name       = Kapiolani Medical Center for Women and Children\n| Org/Group  = <!-- optional -->\n| Image      = <!-- optional -->\n| Caption    = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo       = Kapiolani Medical Center logo.svg\n| Location   = [[Honolulu, Hawaii|Honolulu]]\n| Region     = Oahu\n| State      = Hawaii\n| Country    = US\n| Coordinates =\n| HealthCare = Community\n| Funding    = <!-- Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public -->\n| Type       = Non-profit\n| Speciality = [[Maternity]] and [[Pediatrics]]\n| Standards  = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency  = Yes\n| Helipad     = <!-- No -->\n| Affiliation = <!-- No -->\n| Patron      = <!-- 'None' or the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| Network     = [[Hawaii Pacific Health]]\n| Beds        = 207\n| Founded     = 1978\n| Closed      = <!-- optional -->\n| Website     = http://www.kapiolani.org <!-- 'None' or http URL -->\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n\n[[File:A Woman with a Baby at the Kapiolani Maternity Home.jpg|thumb|A woman with a baby at the Kapiolani Maternity Home around the twenty-first anniversary in 1912]]\n[[File:Obama birth announcement.jpg|150px|thumb|[[Barack Obama]] birth announcement]]\n[[File:Mom and Premature Baby at Kapiolani.jpg|thumb|A new mother holds her baby who was [[Preterm birth|born 10 weeks premature]] at Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center]]\n'''Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children''' is part of [[Hawaii Pacific Health]]'s network of hospitals. It is located in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]], within the residential inner-city district of [[Makiki]]. Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center is Hawaii's only [[children's hospital]] with a  team of physicians and nurses and specialized technology trained specifically to care for children, from infants to young adults. It is the state's only 24-hour pediatric [[emergency department]], pediatric intensive care unit and adolescent unit.\n\nThe facility was founded by [[Queen Kapiolani|Queen Kapi{{okina}}olani]] as the Kapi{{okina}}olani Maternity Home in 1890 for which she held bazaars and [[luau]]s to raise $8,000 needed to start the Home. It has since changed its name several times. Kauikeolani Children\u2019s Hospital opened in 1909 named for [[Emma Kauike\u014dlani Wilcox|Emma Kauike\u014dlani Napoleon Mahelona]] (1862\u20131931), the wife of [[Albert Spencer Wilcox]] (1844\u20131919).<ref>{{cite book |author=Nellist, George F. (ed.) |year=1925 |chapter= Albert Spencer Wilcox |title=The story of Hawaii and its builders |location=Honolulu |publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |chapter-url=http://files.usgwarchives.net/hi/statewide/bios/wilcox64bs.txt |accessdate=September 26, 2010}}</ref>  In 1978, it merged with Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital to become Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children.<ref>{{cite web |author= |year=2009 |title=100 years of caring for children |url=http://www.kapiolanigift.org/timeline/index.html |location=Honolulu |publisher=Kapiolani Health Foundation |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Kessing, Alice |date=August 19, 2009 |title=Queen Kapi'olani's living gift to island keiki |newspaper=[[MidWeek]] |location=Honolulu |url=http://www.midweek.com/content/story/midweek_coverstory/queen_kapiolanis_living_gift_to_island_keiki/P1/ |accessdate=October 1, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430151312/http://www.midweek.com/content/story/midweek_coverstory/queen_kapiolanis_living_gift_to_island_keiki/P1 |archive-date=April 30, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Hawaii Pacific Health |date=August 26, 2009 |title=Kapi'olani Hospital's '100 years \u2013 over 1 million lives' celebration |location=Honolulu |publisher=[[KGMB]] |url=http://kgmb9.com/main/content/view/20536/108/ |accessdate=October 1, 2009 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Historical timeline==\n\n===Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital===\n* In 1884, [[Victoria Kinoiki Kekaulike|Princess Kekaulike]] died and willed her home, ''Ululani'', as the site of a proposed [[maternity home]] to help Hawaiian mothers.\n* In 1890, after the princess's sister, [[Queen Kapiolani|Queen Kapi{{okina}}olani]], raised $8,000 through bazaars and luaus, she founded the '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Home of the Ho{{okina}}oulu and Ho{{okina}}ola Lahui Society''' (society to propagate and perpetuate the race), located at Beretania and Makiki streets, to provide a maternity home for Hawaiian women. The five-bedroom home was opened on June 14, 1890, by [[Kal\u0101kaua|King Kal\u0101kaua]] and Queen Kapi{{okina}}olani. Only six babies were born at the home the first year since Native Hawaiian women remained suspicious of doctors and institutions.\n* In 1917, the society purchased the adjacent August Dreier property southeast of ''Ululani'' on Beretania Street.\n* In 1918, the home moved to a two-story house with 25 beds at 1538 S. Beretania Street, changed its name to the '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Maternity Home''', and opened its doors to women of other than Hawaiian descent.\n* In 1927, the trustees purchased the property of Dr. John Whitney on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham streets to build a new maternity home.\n* In 1928, groundbreaking ceremonies for the new maternity home were held on June 28.\n* In 1929, the home moved on March 26 to a new larger building with 50 beds (in twenty-two private rooms, four 2-bedrooms, and two wards) located on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham streets and expanded its functions to include non-infectious gynecological problems. The original Whitney home was converted to a nurses' home.\n* In 1931, its name was changed to the '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Maternity and Gynecological Hospital'''.\n* In 1939, after purchasing the adjacent Spalding property south of the hospital on Punahou Street, the Spalding home was converted into a nurses' home named the Kekaulike Nurses' Home.\n* In 1945, the hospital, at 1611 Bingham Street, finished construction of the two-story Ewa wing that doubled its capacity to 110 beds.\n* In 1957, the hospital completed a new and enlarged nursery.\n* In 1961, future [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] was born in the hospital on August 4.<ref>{{cite news |author=Maraniss, David |date=August 24, 2008 |title=Though Obama had to leave to find himself, it is Hawaii that made his rise possible |newspaper=The Washington Post |page=A22 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/23/AR2008082301620.html |accessdate=June 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Serafin, Peter |date=March 21, 2004 |title=Punahou grad stirs up Illinois politics |newspaper=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |url=http://archives.starbulletin.com/2004/03/21/news/story4.html |accessdate=June 28, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Hoover, Will |date=November 9, 2008 |title=Obama's Hawaii boyhood homes drawing gawkers |newspaper=The Honolulu Advertiser |page=A1 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Nov/09/ln/hawaii811090361.html |accessdate=June 28, 2009 |quote=Birthplaces and boyhood homes of U.S. presidents have been duly noted and honored}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |date=January 24, 2009 |title=Kapi' olani Health Foundation, The Centennial Dinner January 24, 2009 |location=Honolulu |publisher=Kapiolani Health Foundation |url=http://www.kapiolanigift.org/the_centennial_dinner.aspx |accessdate=June 22, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Nakaso, Dan |date=December 22, 2008 | title=Twin sisters, Obama on parallel paths for years |newspaper=The Honolulu Advertiser |page=B1 |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2008/Dec/22/ln/hawaii812220320.html |accessdate=March 1, 2009}}</ref>\n* In 1966, the hospital completed a new four-story Lani Ward Booth wing on Punahou Street, with the top two floors left as shells, capacity remained at 110 beds.\n* In 1970, the hospital finished the fourth floor of the Lani Booth wing on Punahou Street, capacity increased to 138 beds.\n* In 1971, its name was changed to '''Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital'''.\n* In 1974, the hospital began a major rebuilding project, adding an eleven-story hospital and medical office tower on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham Streets, a three-story building, and a parking structure for a combined Kapi{{okina}}olani/Children's Medical Center.\n* In 1976, the new tower was dedicated and Kapi{{okina}}olani patients were moved to its second and fourth floors.\n* In 1977, a section of the original 1929 building was torn down and tiles from its roof were sold to commemorate the 145,000 babies born under it from 1929 to 1977.\n\n===Kauikeolani Children's Hospital===\n[[File:Kapiolani Neonatal ICU.jpg|thumb|The [[Neonatal intensive-care unit|Neonatal Intensive Care Unit]] (NICU) at Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center]]\n* In 1908, [[Albert Spencer Wilcox]] (1844\u20131919) gave $55,000 and other private subscribers gave an additional $50,000 to buy several acres of land and erect a two-story comparatively small, homelike children's hospital (with preference given to Hawaiian children) at 226 N. Kuakini Street, named after Wilcox's wife, Emma Kauikeolani Napoliean Mahelona (1862\u20131931). A maternity service was soon after added to the hospital.\n* In 1929, the maternity service at the hospital was discontinued.\n* In 1950, a new, modern two-story hospital building with a capacity of 100 beds replaced the original building.\n* In 1953, the Rehabilitation Center of Hawaii was established by the Kauikeolani Children's Hospital Foundation.\n* In 1969, the rehabilitation center was renamed the Pacific Institute of Rehabilitation Medicine.\n* In 1975, the rehabilitation center separated from Kauikeolani Children's Hospital to become the independent Rehabilitation Hospital of the Pacific, which expanded into the 1950 Kauikeolani Children's Hospital building after the latter relocated to Kapi{{okina}}olani/Children's Medical Center on September 15, 1978.\n\n===Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children===\n* In 1976, Kapi{{okina}}olani Hospital and Kauikenolani Children's Hospital began a protracted, decade-long merger.\n* In 1978, Kauikeolani Children's Hospital moved into the new eleven-story (226-bed, 108-bassinet) '''Kapi{{okina}}olani/Children's Medical Center''' tower located at 1319 Punahou Street on the southeast corner of Punahou and Bingham streets\u2014initially with separate entrances for the pediatricians on Bingham Street and the obstetricians on Punahou Street.\n* In 1984, the medical staff and board of directors of the two former hospitals were merged.\n* In 1986, the two former hospitals formally completed their merger.\n* In 1989, Kapi{{okina}}olani purchased for $76 million the new 116-bed [[Kapiolani Medical Center at Pali Momi|Pali Momi Medical Center]] in [[Aiea, Hawaii|Aiea]], built by Health Care International, six months after it opened.\n* In 2001, Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center for Women and Children and Kapi{{okina}}olani Medical Center at Pali Momi in Aiea merged with [[Wilcox Health|Wilcox Memorial Hospital]] in [[Lihue, Hawaii|Lihue]] on the Hawaiian island of [[Kauai]] (founded in 1938) and the [[Straub Clinic & Hospital]] (founded in 1921) on King Street, under a new parent company, [[Hawaii Pacific Health]].\n\n== References ==\n===Sources===\n* {{cite book |author1=Yardley, Maili |author2=Rogers, Miriam |year=1984 |title=The history of Kapiolani Hospital |location=Honolulu |publisher=Topgallant Pub. Co. |isbn=0-914916-62-9 |url=https://archive.org/details/hawaiicooksislan00yard }}\n* {{cite book |author=Schnack, Ferdinand J.H. |year=1915 |title=The aloha guide: the standard handbook of Honolulu and the Hawaiian Islands |url=https://archive.org/details/alohaguidestand02schngoog |location=Honolulu |publisher=Honolulu Star-Bulletin |page=[https://archive.org/details/alohaguidestand02schngoog/page/n154 150] |oclc=12657550}}\n* {{cite book |author=Allen, Gwenfread E. |year=1950 |title=Hawaii's war years, 1941\u20131945 |location=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii |page=339 |isbn=0-8371-5331-X}}\n* {{cite book |author=Catton, Margaret Mary Louise |year=1959 |title=Social service in Hawaii |location=Palo Alto, Calif. |publisher=Pacific Books |pages=99\u2013101, 102\u2013103, 289 |oclc=1970774}}\n* {{cite book |author=Lewis, Frances R. Hegglund |year=1969 |title=History of nursing in Hawaii |location=Node, Wyo. |publisher=Germann-Kilmer |pages=68, 104 |oclc=11323826}}\n* {{cite book |author1=Bowers, John Z. |author2=Purcell, Elizabeth |year=1978 |title=New medical schools at home and abroad: report of a Macy conference |location=New York |publisher=Josiah Macy, Jr. Foundation |page=73 |isbn=0-914362-26-7}}\n* {{cite book |author=Lipp, Martin R. |year=1991 |title=Medical landmarks USA: a travel guide to historic sites, architectural gems, remarkable museums and libraries, and other places of health related interest |location=New York |publisher=McGraw-Hill, Health Professions Div. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/medicallandmarks0000lipp/page/310 310\u2013311] |isbn=0-07-037974-2 |url=https://archive.org/details/medicallandmarks0000lipp/page/310 }}\n* {{cite web |author=. |date=March 8, 2010 |title=Final Environmental Assessment (FEA): Proposed improvements to Kapliolani Medical Center for Women and Children (December 2009) |location=Honolulu |publisher=Office of Environmental Quality Control, Department of Health, State of Hawaii |url=http://oeqc.doh.hawaii.gov/Shared%20Documents/EA_and_EIS_Online_Library/Oahu/2010s/2010-03-08-OA-FEA-Kapiolani-Med-