{"title_page": "Kankakee State Hospital", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Shapiro Developmental Center<br/> <small>''formerly Kankakee State Hospital''</small>\n| Org/Group   = <!-- optional -->\n| Image       = Kankakee Hospital.jpg\n| image_size  = 225 \n| Caption     = The hospital in 1893\n| image alt   = The hospital in 1893\n| map_type    = Illinois\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.1055021|-87.8671829|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n| map_caption = Shown in Kankakee\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- optional -->\n| Location    = 100 East Jeffery Street\n| Region      = [[Kankakee, Illinois|Kankakee]]\n| State       = Illinois\n| Country     = United States\n| HealthCare  = [[State hospital]]\n| Type        = Specialist\n| Speciality  = Developmental Center\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Affiliation =\n| Beds        = \n| Founded     = {{start date|1879|09|04}}\n| Closed      = \n| Website     = <!-- 'None' or http URL -->\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Samuel H. Shapiro Developmental Center''', formerly named the '''Kankakee State Hospital''', is a developmental center in [[Kankakee, Illinois|Kankakee]], [[Illinois]], on the banks of the [[Kankakee River]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1877, the [[Illinois General Assembly|General Assembly]] established the '''Illinois Eastern Hospital for the Insane''' and empowered the Governor to appoint a seven-member commission to select a site within northeastern Illinois on which to locate the institution. After selection of a site in Kankakee, three trustees were appointed by the Governor to supervise planning and construction, choose a superintendent, and operate the hospital, subject to inspection by the Board of State Commissioners of Public Charities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~asylums/kankakee_il/index.html|title=Kankakee State Hospital |website=Historic Asylums of America |publisher=RootsWeb |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital opened on September 4, 1879, and began to operate a training school for nurses in 1886. When the Board of State Commissioners of Public Charities was abolished in 1909, the institute was reorganized and renamed '''Kankakee State Hospital''', effective January 1, 1910.\n\nIn 1917, the Department of Public Welfare assumed responsibility for the Kankakee State Hospital and retained control until the creation of the Department of Mental Health in 1961 (L. 1961, p.&nbsp;2666). On May 10, 1974, the institution became a center for the care and treatment of the developmentally disabled only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=58720 |title=Shapiro Developmental Center Profile |publisher=[[Illinois Department of Human Services]] |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shapiro Developmental Center: Limited Scope Compliance Examination|url=http://www.auditor.illinois.gov/Audit-Reports/Compliance-Agency-List/DHS/Shapiro-DC/FY09-DHS-Shapiro-DC-Comp-digest.htm |publisher=State of Illinois, Office of the Auditor General|accessdate=28 August 2013|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> All other patients were transferred to other mental health facilities and the institution became the Shapiro Developmental Center.  It was renamed the '''Samuel H. Shapiro Developmental Center''' in honor of the Illinois Governor, [[Samuel H. Shapiro]] (1968\u20131969), who had resided in Kankakee.\n\n==Today==\nAs of the end of fiscal year 2010, the center had an annual budget expenditure of {{USD|68,111,000}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=54252|title=Shapiro Developmental Center: FY 2010 Actual Expenditure|accessdate=28 August 2013|publisher=[[Illinois Department of Human Services]]}}</ref> As of the end of fiscal year 2008, the center had 1,119 employees, 587 residents and an annual cost per resident of $175,844.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shapiro Developmental Center: Report Digest|url=http://www.auditor.illinois.gov/Audit-Reports/Compliance-Agency-List/DHS/Shapiro-DC/FY09-DHS-Shapiro-DC-Comp-digest.pdf|publisher=State of Illinois, Office of the Auditor General|accessdate=28 August 2013|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> The Shapiro Center was generating and submitting to the state treasury, 65% of its total operational costs.\n\nThere are underground utility tunnels leading from building to building in the facility. These tunnels were similar to nearby [[Manteno State Hospital]]'s tunnels. This is a result of having a central steam plant for building heating, and it is typical of hospitals constructed under the [[Kirkbride Plan]].\n\n==Notable staff==\n*[[Adolf Meyer (psychiatrist)|Adolf Meyer]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{GNIS|id=411306|name=Shapiro Developmental Center}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.asylumprojects.org/index.php?title=Kankakee_State_Hospital Kankakee State info & history]\n*[http://www.vimeo.com/kirkbrideshd/Kankakee High Definition video from Kirkbrides HD]\n\n{{Illinois State Hospitals}}\n{{Kirkbride Plan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1879]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kankakee County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1879]]\n[[Category:Kankakee, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Shapiro Developmental Center<br/> <small>''formerly Kankakee State Hospital''</small>\n| Org/Group   = <!-- optional -->\n| Image       = Kankakee Hospital.jpg\n| image_size  = 225 \n| Caption     = The hospital in 1893\n| image alt   = The hospital in 1893\n| map_type    = Illinois\n| coordinates = {{coord|41.1055021|-87.8671829|region:US-IL|display=inline,title}}\n| map_caption = Shown in Kankakee\n| Logo        = <!-- optional -->\n| Logo Size   = <!-- optional -->\n| Location    = 100 East Jeffery Street\n| Region      = [[Kankakee, Illinois|Kankakee]]\n| State       = Illinois\n| Country     = United States\n| HealthCare  = [[State hospital]]\n| Type        = Specialist\n| Speciality  = Developmental Center\n| Standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| Emergency   = \n| Affiliation =\n| Beds        = \n| Founded     = {{start date|1879|09|04}}\n| Closed      = \n| Website     = <!-- 'None' or http URL -->\n| Wiki-Links  = <!-- optional -->\n}}\n'''Samuel H. Shapiro Developmental Center''', formerly named the '''Kankakee State Hospital''', is a developmental center in [[Kankakee, Illinois|Kankakee]], [[Illinois]], on the banks of the [[Kankakee River]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1877, the [[Illinois General Assembly|General Assembly]] established the '''Illinois Eastern Hospital for the Insane''' and empowered the Governor to appoint a seven-member commission to select a site within northeastern Illinois on which to locate the institution. After selection of a site in Kankakee, three trustees were appointed by the Governor to supervise planning and construction, choose a superintendent, and operate the hospital, subject to inspection by the Board of State Commissioners of Public Charities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~asylums/kankakee_il/index.html|title=Kankakee State Hospital |website=Historic Asylums of America |publisher=RootsWeb |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital opened on September 4, 1879, and began to operate a training school for nurses in 1886. When the Board of State Commissioners of Public Charities was abolished in 1909, the institute was reorganized and renamed '''Kankakee State Hospital''', effective January 1, 1910.\n\nIn 1917, the Department of Public Welfare assumed responsibility for the Kankakee State Hospital and retained control until the creation of the Department of Mental Health in 1961 (L. 1961, p.&nbsp;2666). On May 10, 1974, the institution became a center for the care and treatment of the developmentally disabled only.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=58720 |title=Shapiro Developmental Center Profile |publisher=[[Illinois Department of Human Services]] |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Shapiro Developmental Center: Limited Scope Compliance Examination|url=http://www.auditor.illinois.gov/Audit-Reports/Compliance-Agency-List/DHS/Shapiro-DC/FY09-DHS-Shapiro-DC-Comp-digest.htm |publisher=State of Illinois, Office of the Auditor General|accessdate=28 August 2013|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> All other patients were transferred to other mental health facilities and the institution became the Shapiro Developmental Center.  It was renamed the '''Samuel H. Shapiro Developmental Center''' in honor of the Illinois Governor, [[Samuel H. Shapiro]] (1968\u20131969), who had resided in Kankakee.\n\n==Today==\nAs of the end of fiscal year 2010, the center had an annual budget expenditure of {{USD|68,111,000}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dhs.state.il.us/page.aspx?item=54252|title=Shapiro Developmental Center: FY 2010 Actual Expenditure|accessdate=28 August 2013|publisher=[[Illinois Department of Human Services]]}}</ref> As of the end of fiscal year 2008, the center had 1,119 employees, 587 residents and an annual cost per resident of $175,844.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shapiro Developmental Center: Report Digest|url=http://www.auditor.illinois.gov/Audit-Reports/Compliance-Agency-List/DHS/Shapiro-DC/FY09-DHS-Shapiro-DC-Comp-digest.pdf|publisher=State of Illinois, Office of the Auditor General|accessdate=28 August 2013|date=29 June 2010}}</ref> The Shapiro Center was generating and submitting to the state treasury, 65% of its total operational costs.\n\nThere are underground utility tunnels leading from building to building in the facility. These tunnels were similar to nearby [[Manteno State Hospital]]'s tunnels. This is a result of having a central steam plant for building heating, and it is typical of hospitals constructed under the [[Kirkbride Plan]].\n\n==Notable staff==\n*[[Adolf Meyer (psychiatrist)|Adolf Meyer]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{GNIS|id=411306|name=Shapiro Developmental Center}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.asylumprojects.org/index.php?title=Kankakee_State_Hospital Kankakee State info & history]\n*[http://www.vimeo.com/kirkbrideshd/Kankakee High Definition video from Kirkbrides HD]\n\n{{Illinois State Hospitals}}\n{{Kirkbride Plan}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1879]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kankakee County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1879]]\n[[Category:Kankakee, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Psychiatric hospitals in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1879 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kankakee_State_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Kalispell Regional Medical Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name             = Kalispell Regional Medical Center (Montana)\n| map_type         = USA Montana\n| coordinates      = {{coord|48.2145|-114.3240|display=inline,title}}\n| logo             = Kalispell Regional Medical Center 5-19-11.jpg\n| region           = [[Kalispell, Montana|Kalispell]]\n| State            = Montana\n| Country          = US\n| caption          = Improve health, comfort, and life\n| type             = General medical and surgical\n| founded          = Kalispell, United States ({{Start date|1910}})<!-- City, Country ({{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}}) -->\n| founder          = \n| location      = [[Flathead County, Montana]]\n| Helipad          = Yes\n| services         = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.kalispellregional.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Kalispell Regional Medical Center''' is a 138-bed [[hospital]], located at 310 Sunnyview Lane in [[Kalispell, Montana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana\u2019s Flathead Valley|url=http://www.fcvb.org/members.php?catName=kalispell&catId=100&businessName=Kalispell+Regional+Medical+Center&busId=108|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>  The hospital is accredited by the [[Commission on Accreditation of Rehabilitation Facilities]] (CARF)<ref>{{cite web|title=US News Best Hospitals|url=http://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/mt/kalispell-regional-medical-center-6810007|work=[[U.S. News and World Report]]|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1973, the ownership of the Kalispell General Hospital was transferred from the [[Sisters of Mercy]] to the community and the name was then changed to the Kalispell Regional Hospital.  On January 17, 1976, the Kalispell Regional Hospital was completed and ready to render patient care. The old hospital (Kalispell General Hospital) became \"Courthouse East\" and was used by the county for various offices until a new courthouse building could be constructed.  In 1975, A.L.E.R.T.,  [[helicopter]] [[ambulance]] service, flew its first patient.  In 1981, a medical/surgical [[Intensive Care Unit]] was added.  In 1985, Brendan House, an extended care facility, was opened.   In 1987, the Kalispell Regional Hospital became the first in the state of [[Montana]] to install an [[MRI]], a [[cancer]] treatment center was added, and a new freestanding [[Obstetrics]] Department was opened.  In 1989, [[Dialysis]] and [[Rehabilitation hospital|Inpatient Rehabilitation]] facilities were added.  In 1994, Kalispell Regional Healthcare purchased nearly 50 acres adjacent to the hospital.  In 1996, the Kalispell Regional Healthcare opened \"The Summit Community Center for Health Promotion and Fitness\", combining the services of Second Wind (fitness) and the Health Promotion Center (community health education and rehabilitation) into one 84,000 square foot building.  In 1997, Kalispell Regional Hospital changed their name to \"Kalispell Regional Medical Center\".\n\n==Rankings==\nKalispell Regional Medical Center is rated in 28 conditions and procedures by [[Healthgrades]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Healthgrades |url= http://www.healthgrades.com/hospital-directory/montana-mt/Kalispell-Regional-Medical-Center-HGST02A70596270051|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>  Kalispell Regional Medical Center has received an A+ Rating with the [[Better Business Bureau]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Better Business Bureau |url= http://www.bbb.org/eastern-washington/business-reviews/hospitals/kalispell-regional-medical-center-in-kalispell-mt-64199010|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn Spring 2016 The Leapfrog Group's \"Hospital Safety Score\" page scored Kalispell Regional Medical Center as a B.<ref name=HSS>{{cite web|author=Kalispell Regional Medical Center |url=http://www.hospitalsafetyscore.org/h/kalispell-regional-medical-center?findBy=city&city=Kalispell&state_prov=MT |title=Kalispell Regional Medical Center - MT |publisher=Hospital Safety Score |date=2015-04-29 |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of hospitals in Montana]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kalispellregional.org/krmc/ Official Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Montana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n| Name             = Kalispell Regional Medical Center (Montana)\n| map_type         = USA Montana\n| coordinates      = {{coord|48.2145|-114.3240|display=inline,title}}\n| logo             = Kalispell Regional Medical Center 5-19-11.jpg\n| region           = [[Kalispell, Montana|Kalispell]]\n| State            = Montana\n| Country          = US\n| caption          = Improve health, comfort, and life\n| type             = General medical and surgical\n| founded          = Kalispell, United States ({{Start date|1910}})<!-- City, Country ({{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}}) -->\n| founder          = \n| location      = [[Flathead County, Montana]]\n| Helipad          = Yes\n| services         = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.kalispellregional.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Kalispell Regional Medical Center''' is a 138-bed [[hospital]], located at 310 Sunnyview Lane in [[Kalispell, Montana]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana\u2019s Flathead Valley|url=http://www.fcvb.org/members.php?catName=kalispell&catId=100&businessName=Kalispell+Regional+Medical+Center&busId=108|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>  The hospital is accredited by the [[Commission on Accreditation of Rehabilitation Facilities]] (CARF)<ref>{{cite web|title=US News Best Hospitals|url=http://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/mt/kalispell-regional-medical-center-6810007|work=[[U.S. News and World Report]]|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1973, the ownership of the Kalispell General Hospital was transferred from the [[Sisters of Mercy]] to the community and the name was then changed to the Kalispell Regional Hospital.  On January 17, 1976, the Kalispell Regional Hospital was completed and ready to render patient care. The old hospital (Kalispell General Hospital) became \"Courthouse East\" and was used by the county for various offices until a new courthouse building could be constructed.  In 1975, A.L.E.R.T.,  [[helicopter]] [[ambulance]] service, flew its first patient.  In 1981, a medical/surgical [[Intensive Care Unit]] was added.  In 1985, Brendan House, an extended care facility, was opened.   In 1987, the Kalispell Regional Hospital became the first in the state of [[Montana]] to install an [[MRI]], a [[cancer]] treatment center was added, and a new freestanding [[Obstetrics]] Department was opened.  In 1989, [[Dialysis]] and [[Rehabilitation hospital|Inpatient Rehabilitation]] facilities were added.  In 1994, Kalispell Regional Healthcare purchased nearly 50 acres adjacent to the hospital.  In 1996, the Kalispell Regional Healthcare opened \"The Summit Community Center for Health Promotion and Fitness\", combining the services of Second Wind (fitness) and the Health Promotion Center (community health education and rehabilitation) into one 84,000 square foot building.  In 1997, Kalispell Regional Hospital changed their name to \"Kalispell Regional Medical Center\".\n\n==Rankings==\nKalispell Regional Medical Center is rated in 28 conditions and procedures by [[Healthgrades]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Healthgrades |url= http://www.healthgrades.com/hospital-directory/montana-mt/Kalispell-Regional-Medical-Center-HGST02A70596270051|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>  Kalispell Regional Medical Center has received an A+ Rating with the [[Better Business Bureau]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Better Business Bureau |url= http://www.bbb.org/eastern-washington/business-reviews/hospitals/kalispell-regional-medical-center-in-kalispell-mt-64199010|accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn Spring 2016 The Leapfrog Group's \"Hospital Safety Score\" page scored Kalispell Regional Medical Center as a B.<ref name=HSS>{{cite web|author=Kalispell Regional Medical Center |url=http://www.hospitalsafetyscore.org/h/kalispell-regional-medical-center?findBy=city&city=Kalispell&state_prov=MT |title=Kalispell Regional Medical Center - MT |publisher=Hospital Safety Score |date=2015-04-29 |accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of hospitals in Montana]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kalispellregional.org/krmc/ Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Hospitals in Montana]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalispell_Regional_Medical_Center"}
{"title_page": "Kaleida Health", "text_new": "{{short description|Non-profit healthcare network in Buffalo, New York, USA}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=December 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}}\n{{third-party|date=December 2017}}\n}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Kaleida Health\n| logo = KaleidaLogo.jpg\n| caption = \n| alt = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = [[Healthcare industry|Health care]]\n| predecessor = CFG Health System<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite web|title=Kaleida Health, Inc.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=139066129|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg LP|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n| foundation = [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States<br>{{start date and age|1998}}<ref name=\"bloomberg\" />\n| founder = \n| location_city = [[Buffalo, New York]]\n| location_country = United States\n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| area_served = [[Western New York]]\n| key_people = Jody L. Lomeo<ref name=\"bloomberg\" />\n| products = \n| production = \n| services = [[Hospital network]]\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 9675 <ref>https://www.kaleidahealth.org/kyi/pdf/We-Are-Kaleida-Health.pdf</ref>\n| divisions = See prose\n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|kaleida.org}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| bodystyle = \n}}\n[[File:Buffalo General Hospital 2012.JPG|thumb|Buffalo General Hospital (viewed from Ellicott Street)]]\n[[FIle:Oishei1.jpg|thumb|Oishei Children's Hospital (viewed from Ellicott Street)]]\n\n'''Kaleida Health''', founded in 1998, is a not-for-profit healthcare network that manages five hospitals in the [[Buffalo\u2013Niagara Falls metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"bloomberg\"/>\n\n==Facilities==\nKaleida Health runs the Buffalo General Medical Center, a hospital on the premises of the [[Buffalo Niagara Medical Campus]]. It was founded on its current site in the 19th century<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Diehl|first=Lois Mastin|date=1901|title=A History of the Buffalo General Hospital Training-School for Nurses|jstor=3402380|journal=The American Journal of Nursing|volume=1|issue=11|pages=790\u2013795|doi=10.2307/3402380}}</ref> and has undergone expansions ever since, including one in the 1986 that added a 16-story tower to the main complex.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The AJN Guide to Nursing Career Opportunities|last=|first=|date=1990|publisher=American Journal of Nursing Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=189|language=en}}</ref>  The hospital had 24,000 inpatient visits in 2016.<ref name=\"Beds\">{{cite news|last1=Drury|first1=Tracey|title=Kaleida works to keep excess beds from Children's|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2017/08/17/kaleida-works-to-keep-excess-beds-from-childrens.html|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=17 August 2017}}</ref> The interior lobby was remodeled, and the exterior of the building was repainted in 2017 to match the color scheme of newer facilities on the campus, at a cost of $2 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Drury|first1=Tracey|title=Buffalo General gets face-lift inside and out|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2017/09/25/buffalo-general-gets-face-lift-inside-and-out.html|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Beds\" />\n\nKaleida also runs the John R. Oishei Children's Hospital, a [[children's hospital]] that is also at the Buffalo Niagara Medical Campus.  It opened in November 2017 and cost  $270 million to build.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Drury|first1=Tracey|title=Patient by patient, Oishei Children's Hospital comes online|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2017/11/10/patient-by-patient-oishei-childrens-hospital-comes.html|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American Business Journals|date=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis2017\">{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Henry L.|title=How the new Oishei Children's Hospital came to be|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/11/04/how-the-new-oishei-childrens-hospital-came-to-be/|work=The Buffalo News|publisher=Berkshire Hathaway|date=4 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Robinson2017\">{{cite news|last1=Robinson|first1=Karen|title=Take a look inside Buffalo's new Children's Hospital|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/11/02/take-a-look-inside-buffalos-new-childrens-hospital/|work=The Buffalo News|publisher=Berkshire Hathaway|date=2 November 2017}}</ref> There are 185 beds, including 64 neonatal units, fourteen operating rooms, an indoor garden, and [[skyway]] connections to neighboring [[Buffalo General Hospital]] and [[Conventus]].<ref name=\"Robinson2017\" />  The hospital broke ground in 2015 and was designed by [[Shepley Bulfinch]] and built by [[Turner Construction]].<ref name=\"Robinson2017\" />\n[[File:Gates Vascular Institute.JPG|thumb|right|[[Gates Vascular Institute]]]]\n\nKaleida and the [[State University of New York at Buffalo]] jointly built the [[Gates Vascular Institute]] building which was completed in 2012; the lower floors house a clinical facility run by Kaleida that includes an emergency room, outpatient, inpatient, and medical imaging facilities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaleida Health Gates Vascular Institute / Cannon Design|url=http://www.archdaily.com/346337/kaleida-health-gates-vascular-institute-cannon-design|website=ArchDaily|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017 Kaleida Health oversees Upper Allegheny Health System, which comprises Brooks Memorial Hospital, [[Lakeshore Hospital]], Olean General, Bradford Regional Medical Center, and Cuba Memorial Hospital.\n\n== Patient Safety Concerns ==\nA report produced by [[Consumer Reports]] in July 2015 on the prevalence of hospital-acquired infections gave Kaleida hospitals a below average ranking in 4 of the report's 5 categories.  The ranking was based on hospital-reported data provided to federal [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] between October 2013 and September 2014.<ref>[http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/consumer-reports-study-on-infections-rates-several-wny-hospitals-below-average-20150729 Consumer Reports study on infections rates several WNY hospitals below-average]</ref>\n \t\nKaleida Health was also cited by [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] for having high rates of infections and other patient-safety problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2015/12/16/kaleida-mercy-hospital-face-medicare-penalties-for-high-infection-rates/|title=Kaleida, Mercy Hospital face Medicare penalties for high infection rates|last=Davis|first=Henry L.|date=2015-12-16|website=The Buffalo News|language=en-us|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>  The Hospital Acquired Conditions Reduction Program, which was created as part of the [[Affordable Care Act]], seeks to incentivize hospitals to improve patient safety by measuring rates of hospital-acquired infection and other patient safety metrics and then penalizing hospitals that perform poorly.  As a result of this program Kaleida Health has been penalized more than $1 million in 2016 through reduced Medicare payments.<ref>[http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/medical/kaleida-mercy-hospital-face-medicare-penalties-for-high-infection-rates-20151216 Kaleida, Mercy Hospital face Medicare penalties for high infection rates]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://kaleidahealth.org Official website]\n{{New York Trauma Centers}}{{Coord|42.9008896|-78.8679687|type:landmark_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1998 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Erie County, New York]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1998]]\n[[Category:Healthcare in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Hospital networks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Buffalo, New York]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Non-profit healthcare network in Buffalo, New York, USA}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=December 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=December 2017}}\n{{third-party|date=December 2017}}\n}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Kaleida Health\n| logo = KaleidaLogo.jpg\n| caption = \n| alt = \n| trading_name = <!-- d/b/a/, doing business as - if different from legal name above -->\n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| industry = [[Healthcare industry|Health care]]\n| predecessor = CFG Health System<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite web|title=Kaleida Health, Inc.: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=139066129|website=Bloomberg|publisher=Bloomberg LP|accessdate=12 December 2017}}</ref>\n| foundation = [[Buffalo, New York|Buffalo]], [[New York (state)|New York]], United States<br>{{start date and age|1998}}<ref name=\"bloomberg\" />\n| founder = \n| location_city = [[Buffalo, New York]]\n| location_country = United States\n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices, etc. -->\n| area_served = [[Western New York]]\n| key_people = Jody L. Lomeo<ref name=\"bloomberg\" />\n| products = \n| production = \n| services = [[Hospital network]]\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| owner = \n| num_employees = 9675 <ref>https://www.kaleidahealth.org/kyi/pdf/We-Are-Kaleida-Health.pdf</ref>\n| divisions = See prose\n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{URL|kaleida.org}}\n| footnotes = \n| intl = \n| bodystyle = \n}}\n[[File:Buffalo General Hospital 2012.JPG|thumb|Buffalo General Hospital (viewed from Ellicott Street)]]\n[[FIle:Oishei1.jpg|thumb|Oishei Children's Hospital (viewed from Ellicott Street)]]\n\n'''Kaleida Health''', founded in 1998, is a not-for-profit healthcare network that manages five hospitals in the [[Buffalo\u2013Niagara Falls metropolitan area]].<ref name=\"bloomberg\"/>\n\n==Facilities==\nKaleida Health runs the Buffalo General Medical Center, a hospital on the premises of the [[Buffalo Niagara Medical Campus]]. It was founded on its current site in the 19th century<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Diehl|first=Lois Mastin|date=1901|title=A History of the Buffalo General Hospital Training-School for Nurses|jstor=3402380|journal=The American Journal of Nursing|volume=1|issue=11|pages=790\u2013795|doi=10.2307/3402380}}</ref> and has undergone expansions ever since, including one in the 1986 that added a 16-story tower to the main complex.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The AJN Guide to Nursing Career Opportunities|last=|first=|date=1990|publisher=American Journal of Nursing Company|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=189|language=en}}</ref>  The hospital had 24,000 inpatient visits in 2016.<ref name=\"Beds\">{{cite news|last1=Drury|first1=Tracey|title=Kaleida works to keep excess beds from Children's|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2017/08/17/kaleida-works-to-keep-excess-beds-from-childrens.html|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=17 August 2017}}</ref> The interior lobby was remodeled, and the exterior of the building was repainted in 2017 to match the color scheme of newer facilities on the campus, at a cost of $2 million.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Drury|first1=Tracey|title=Buffalo General gets face-lift inside and out|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2017/09/25/buffalo-general-gets-face-lift-inside-and-out.html|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American City Business Journals|date=25 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Beds\" />\n\nKaleida also runs the John R. Oishei Children's Hospital, a [[children's hospital]] that is also at the Buffalo Niagara Medical Campus.  It opened in November 2017 and cost  $270 million to build.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Drury|first1=Tracey|title=Patient by patient, Oishei Children's Hospital comes online|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/buffalo/news/2017/11/10/patient-by-patient-oishei-childrens-hospital-comes.html|work=Buffalo Business First|publisher=American Business Journals|date=10 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis2017\">{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Henry L.|title=How the new Oishei Children's Hospital came to be|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/11/04/how-the-new-oishei-childrens-hospital-came-to-be/|work=The Buffalo News|publisher=Berkshire Hathaway|date=4 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Robinson2017\">{{cite news|last1=Robinson|first1=Karen|title=Take a look inside Buffalo's new Children's Hospital|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/11/02/take-a-look-inside-buffalos-new-childrens-hospital/|work=The Buffalo News|publisher=Berkshire Hathaway|date=2 November 2017}}</ref> There are 185 beds, including 64 neonatal units, fourteen operating rooms, an indoor garden, and [[skyway]] connections to neighboring [[Buffalo General Hospital]] and [[Conventus]].<ref name=\"Robinson2017\" />  The hospital broke ground in 2015 and was designed by [[Shepley Bulfinch]] and built by [[Turner Construction]].<ref name=\"Robinson2017\" />\n[[File:Gates Vascular Institute.JPG|thumb|right|[[Gates Vascular Institute]]]]\n\nKaleida and the [[State University of New York at Buffalo]] jointly built the [[Gates Vascular Institute]] building which was completed in 2012; the lower floors house a clinical facility run by Kaleida that includes an emergency room, outpatient, inpatient, and medical imaging facilities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kaleida Health Gates Vascular Institute / Cannon Design|url=http://www.archdaily.com/346337/kaleida-health-gates-vascular-institute-cannon-design|website=ArchDaily|accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2017 Kaleida Health oversees Upper Allegheny Health System, which comprises Brooks Memorial Hospital, [[Lakeshore Hospital]], Olean General, Bradford Regional Medical Center, and Cuba Memorial Hospital.\n\n== Patient Safety Concerns ==\nA report produced by [[Consumer Reports]] in July 2015 on the prevalence of hospital-acquired infections gave Kaleida hospitals a below average ranking in 4 of the report's 5 categories.  The ranking was based on hospital-reported data provided to federal [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] between October 2013 and September 2014.<ref>[http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/consumer-reports-study-on-infections-rates-several-wny-hospitals-below-average-20150729 Consumer Reports study on infections rates several WNY hospitals below-average]</ref>\n \t\nKaleida Health was also cited by [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] for having high rates of infections and other patient-safety problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://buffalonews.com/2015/12/16/kaleida-mercy-hospital-face-medicare-penalties-for-high-infection-rates/|title=Kaleida, Mercy Hospital face Medicare penalties for high infection rates|last=Davis|first=Henry L.|date=2015-12-16|website=The Buffalo News|language=en-us|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref>  The Hospital Acquired Conditions Reduction Program, which was created as part of the [[Affordable Care Act]], seeks to incentivize hospitals to improve patient safety by measuring rates of hospital-acquired infection and other patient safety metrics and then penalizing hospitals that perform poorly.  As a result of this program Kaleida Health has been penalized more than $1 million in 2016 through reduced Medicare payments.<ref>[http://www.buffalonews.com/city-region/medical/kaleida-mercy-hospital-face-medicare-penalties-for-high-infection-rates-20151216 Kaleida, Mercy Hospital face Medicare penalties for high infection rates]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://kaleidahealth.org Official website]\n{{New York Trauma Centers}}{{Coord|42.9008896|-78.8679687|type:landmark_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:1998 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies based 